    title: 'What is Voice? Understanding Tone and Perspective',
    duration: '45 mins',
    content: `<h2>Every Writer Has a Voice</h2>
<p>When you read a text, you are hearing a <strong>voice</strong>. Not a literal sound, but the personality, attitude, and style that come through in the writing. Voice is what makes one writer sound different from another, even if they are writing about the same topic. Think of it this way: if ten people described the same sunset, you would get ten different descriptions. That difference is voice.</p>

<p>Voice is shaped by three key ingredients: <strong>word choice</strong> (the vocabulary a writer selects), <strong>tone</strong> (the attitude behind the words), and <strong>perspective</strong> (the viewpoint from which the writing comes). Together, these three elements create the unique fingerprint of every piece of writing you will ever read.</p>

<h3>What is Tone?</h3>
<p>Tone is the <strong>attitude</strong> a writer takes towards their subject or audience. It is the emotional colour of the writing. A letter to a friend has a different tone from a letter of complaint to a company. A ghost story has a different tone from a comedy sketch. Learning to identify tone is one of the most important reading skills you will develop.</p>

<div class="key-term"><strong>Key Term: Tone</strong> — The attitude or feeling conveyed by a piece of writing. Tone can be formal, informal, serious, humorous, angry, hopeful, sarcastic, melancholy, or dozens of other moods. It is created through word choice, sentence length, and punctuation.</div>

<p>Consider these two descriptions of a rainy day:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>"The rain hammered against the windows like tiny fists, trapping us inside the grey prison of the afternoon."</em> — The tone here is <strong>frustrated and oppressive</strong>. Words like "hammered," "fists," "trapping," and "prison" create a sense of anger and confinement.</li>
<li><em>"The rain pattered softly on the roof, wrapping the house in a gentle blanket of sound."</em> — The tone here is <strong>calm and comforting</strong>. Words like "pattered," "softly," "wrapping," and "gentle blanket" create warmth and safety.</li>
</ul>

<p>Same weather. Completely different feelings. That is the power of tone.</p>

<h3>What is Perspective?</h3>
<p>Perspective is the <strong>viewpoint</strong> from which a text is written. It determines what the reader can and cannot see. A story told by a child will notice different things from a story told by an adult. A news report written in London about an event in another country will have a different perspective from a report written by someone who was there.</p>

<div class="text-extract">"I could feel the heat of every pair of eyes in the room. My hands trembled as I unfolded the paper. The words blurred. I opened my mouth, but nothing came out."<div class="source">Original example — first-person narrative</div></div>

<p>This passage is written from a <strong>first-person perspective</strong> — we are inside the narrator's head, feeling their fear. We do not know what the audience is thinking; we only know what the speaker experiences. This creates <strong>intimacy and empathy</strong> because we share the narrator's vulnerability.</p>

<div class="examiner-tip"><strong>Examiner Tip:</strong> When asked about voice, always discuss at least two of the three ingredients — word choice, tone, and perspective. Linking them together shows sophisticated understanding. For example: "The writer's use of short, blunt sentences creates a cold, detached tone, which reinforces the narrator's isolated perspective."</div>

<h3>Why Does Voice Matter?</h3>
<p>Voice matters because it is how writers connect with readers. A strong voice makes writing memorable, persuasive, and authentic. When you write, your voice is what makes your work <strong>yours</strong> — not a copy of someone else's style, but something that carries your personality, your experiences, and your way of seeing the world.</p>

<p>Over the next few modules, you will develop your own writing voice by studying how other writers use theirs. You will learn to make deliberate choices about tone, word choice, and perspective so that your writing sounds confident, clear, and unmistakably you.</p>

<div class="common-mistake"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Confusing tone with mood. Tone is the writer's attitude; mood is the feeling created in the reader. They are related but not identical. A writer might use a sarcastic tone, which creates an uneasy mood in the reader. Always be precise about which one you are discussing.</div>`,
